16:18.120 --> 16:18.960
to silence him.

16:19.160 --> 16:19.840
For most people,

16:19.940 --> 16:20.440
it's a muzzle.

16:20.820 --> 16:21.880
But Jake turns it

16:21.880 --> 16:23.160
into a Trojan horse.

16:23.620 --> 16:25.520
He teams up with a ghostwriter

16:25.520 --> 16:27.340
and begins crafting the manuscript,

16:27.340 --> 16:30.000
then slices it into 20-page chunks

16:30.000 --> 16:31.760
and feeds them to DOPSR.

16:32.180 --> 16:33.960
The first round took six months

16:33.960 --> 16:35.140
and came back

16:35.140 --> 16:37.360
with seven pages of redactions.

16:37.920 --> 16:39.540
Instead of killing his story,

16:39.800 --> 16:41.320
the redactions only served

16:41.320 --> 16:42.100
to confirm it.

16:42.620 --> 16:43.080
You see,

16:43.220 --> 16:45.100
Jake used the redaction process

16:45.100 --> 16:45.580
backwards

16:45.580 --> 16:47.420
as a discovery tool.

16:47.420 --> 16:48.100
Normally,

16:48.340 --> 16:49.340
you know it's classified

16:49.340 --> 16:50.420
and you avoid it.

16:50.640 --> 16:52.020
But Jake submitted material

16:52.020 --> 16:53.720
he suspected was classified,

16:54.260 --> 16:54.880
then watched

16:54.880 --> 16:56.520
what the Pentagon blacked out.

16:56.900 --> 16:58.200
By drip-feeding chapters,

16:58.700 --> 17:00.140
he could see which lines

17:00.140 --> 17:01.540
made the Pentagon flinch,

17:01.920 --> 17:02.360
adjust,

17:03.040 --> 17:03.460
probe,

17:03.980 --> 17:05.480
and slip real facts

17:05.480 --> 17:07.180
about the UFO legacy program

17:07.180 --> 17:08.560
into the public domain

17:08.560 --> 17:09.760
under the camouflage

17:09.760 --> 17:10.700
of fiction.

17:11.280 --> 17:11.900
The manuscript

17:11.900 --> 17:13.400
becomes a Trojan horse.

17:13.680 --> 17:15.380
The Pentagon's own bureaucracy

17:15.380 --> 17:17.260
becomes the delivery mechanism.

17:17.820 --> 17:19.080
And buried in the pages

17:19.080 --> 17:20.980
is a trail of breadcrumbs

17:20.980 --> 17:22.680
hidden in plain sight.

17:23.000 --> 17:23.820
For most readers,

17:24.000 --> 17:24.900
it's just a thriller.

17:25.560 --> 17:26.640
But for those who know

17:26.640 --> 17:27.460
what to look for,

17:27.780 --> 17:28.440
it's a cipher

17:28.440 --> 17:30.300
waiting for the right eyes

17:30.300 --> 17:31.240
to crack it open.

17:31.480 --> 17:32.980
And the clock starts ticking.

17:37.220 --> 17:38.640
Out in the badlands,

17:38.860 --> 17:40.540
just north of Kuyame, Mexico,

17:41.060 --> 17:42.940
Earth looks a lot like Mars.

17:42.940 --> 17:44.860
Mesas ripped sideways

17:44.860 --> 17:46.400
from tectonic violence.

17:47.140 --> 17:48.980
Rust and bone-white rock layers

17:48.980 --> 17:50.700
streak down canyon walls.

17:51.280 --> 17:52.920
Boulders sit in bizarrely

17:52.920 --> 17:54.080
impossible stacks

17:54.080 --> 17:55.600
like a Martian sculptor

17:55.600 --> 17:57.300
played Jenga with geology.

17:58.380 --> 18:00.280
There's no light pollution here.

18:00.800 --> 18:01.740
No highway glow.

18:02.200 --> 18:03.280
No city haze.

18:03.700 --> 18:04.740
When the sun drops,

18:05.000 --> 18:05.980
it's just you,

18:06.340 --> 18:07.180
the desert floor,

18:07.640 --> 18:08.840
and the whole galaxy

18:08.840 --> 18:10.120
staring back at you.

18:10.120 --> 18:12.080
Which means if you don't

18:12.080 --> 18:12.920
want to be seen,

18:13.500 --> 18:14.940
this is the perfect place

18:14.940 --> 18:15.740
to disappear.

18:18.660 --> 18:20.920
Welcome to Enigmatic Kuyame,

18:21.420 --> 18:23.920
population 1,230.

18:24.620 --> 18:25.660
On paper,

18:25.900 --> 18:27.440
it's a sleepy border town.

18:28.940 --> 18:30.300
But ask around,

18:30.600 --> 18:32.360
and it's Mexico's Roswell.

18:32.580 --> 18:34.000
And that's not hyperbole.

18:34.000 --> 18:35.480
It's literally the title

18:35.480 --> 18:36.120
of a book

18:36.120 --> 18:37.700
by researchers Noe Torres

18:37.700 --> 18:39.100
and Ruben Uriarte,

18:39.360 --> 18:40.400
who both documented

18:40.400 --> 18:42.300
decades of strange activity

18:42.300 --> 18:43.080
in the area.

18:43.500 --> 18:44.920
Locals constantly talk

18:44.920 --> 18:46.060
about colored lights

18:46.060 --> 18:47.440
that wink in and out

18:47.440 --> 18:48.660
around the mountain peaks.

18:53.500 --> 18:55.680
Little orbs and square objects

18:55.680 --> 18:56.900
that seem to come

18:56.900 --> 18:58.560
out of the landscape itself.

18:58.560 --> 19:01.200
And then there's the big one.

19:02.880 --> 19:04.460
In 1974,

19:04.940 --> 19:06.260
Kuyame became the setting

19:06.260 --> 19:07.700
for one of the strangest

19:07.700 --> 19:09.260
crash stories on record.

19:09.260 --> 19:29.180
A mid-air collision

19:29.180 --> 19:31.120
between a small Mexican plane

19:31.120 --> 19:32.060
and a UFO.

19:34.680 --> 19:36.600
A Mexican recovery team

19:36.600 --> 19:37.680
raced to the site

19:37.680 --> 19:39.060
but never came back.

19:39.260 --> 19:43.360
According to the leaked report

19:43.360 --> 19:45.020
that surfaced in the 90s,

19:45.220 --> 19:46.900
the whole Mexican team

19:46.900 --> 19:47.920
ends up dead.

19:48.340 --> 19:49.440
And the mystery object

19:49.440 --> 19:50.720
is airlifted out

19:50.720 --> 19:51.780
by U.S. forces.

19:54.900 --> 19:56.440
If you're imaginative,

19:56.600 --> 19:57.340
you might wonder

19:57.340 --> 19:58.460
if Kuyame wasn't

19:58.460 --> 19:59.460
just a crash site,

20:00.260 --> 20:02.200
but has long been a sandbox

20:02.200 --> 20:03.960
for clandestine ops.

20:04.600 --> 20:05.560
Perfectly isolated,

20:06.000 --> 20:07.200
with weird geology

20:07.200 --> 20:09.180
very good at hiding doorways

20:09.180 --> 20:09.780
to things

20:09.780 --> 20:09.800
to things

20:09.800 --> 20:10.700
that aren't supposed

20:10.700 --> 20:11.440
to exist.

20:14.560 --> 20:15.500
The locals,

20:15.920 --> 20:16.660
they don't talk

20:16.660 --> 20:17.700
about the lights anymore.

20:18.180 --> 20:18.900
And if you ask

20:18.900 --> 20:19.900
too many questions,

20:20.260 --> 20:21.680
you might find out why.

20:21.680 --> 20:41.500
Alex McEwen, Tier 1 Operator.

20:41.500 --> 20:45.020
11 years in America's most elite units.

20:45.020 --> 20:46.020
Tonight, he's alone.

20:46.020 --> 20:49.760
Tonight, he's alone.

20:50.600 --> 20:52.380
Escorting two dozen refugees

20:52.380 --> 20:54.380
through jagged desert terrain.

20:55.020 --> 20:55.840
Women and children

20:55.840 --> 20:56.680
who will die

20:56.680 --> 20:57.760
if he doesn't get them

20:57.760 --> 20:58.020
to extraction.

20:58.020 --> 21:20.060
They're early,

21:20.060 --> 21:21.040
and his team

21:21.040 --> 21:22.540
is still behind him somewhere.

21:23.200 --> 21:24.600
Extraction without the unit

21:24.600 --> 21:25.580
wasn't the plan.

21:29.060 --> 21:30.020
H1, I copy.

21:30.100 --> 21:30.640
What is your 20?

21:31.320 --> 21:32.180
Alex hits them

21:32.180 --> 21:32.760
with a code

21:32.760 --> 21:33.300
that's known

21:33.300 --> 21:34.620
as a verbal IFF,

21:35.040 --> 21:36.040
a code only people

21:36.040 --> 21:37.540
on this classified op

21:37.540 --> 21:38.180
should know.

21:42.420 --> 21:42.980
Matchbox.

21:43.520 --> 21:45.100
He gets the right answer,

21:45.240 --> 21:46.240
so he waves

21:46.240 --> 21:47.420
the refugees forward.

21:47.420 --> 21:50.120
But here's what Alex

21:50.120 --> 21:50.840
doesn't know.

21:50.960 --> 21:51.680
These refugees

21:51.680 --> 21:52.980
weren't just lucky enough

21:52.980 --> 21:54.600
to have a Tier 1 escort.

21:56.140 --> 21:57.740
Someone very powerful

21:57.740 --> 21:59.000
wanted them here.

22:03.700 --> 22:04.780
Barber claims

22:04.780 --> 22:05.880
that some of these

22:05.880 --> 22:07.420
Black Aerospace programs

22:07.420 --> 22:09.560
had a very specific need.

22:09.880 --> 22:11.080
People untouched

22:11.080 --> 22:12.460
by modern civilization,

22:12.920 --> 22:13.520
often from

22:13.520 --> 22:14.660
Third World countries,

22:15.480 --> 22:17.080
psychically uncorrupted,

22:17.080 --> 22:18.520
and displaced people,

22:19.100 --> 22:19.640
refugees,

22:20.440 --> 22:21.840
victims of natural disaster,

22:22.080 --> 22:22.760
they're perfect.

22:24.460 --> 22:25.120
No passport,

22:25.500 --> 22:26.360
no paper trail,

22:26.600 --> 22:27.580
no one who'd know

22:27.580 --> 22:28.760
if they went missing.

22:29.100 --> 22:31.360
Fed into a UFO legacy operation

22:31.360 --> 22:32.520
that most people

22:32.520 --> 22:33.960
will never hear about.

22:34.220 --> 22:35.500
All the program would need

22:35.500 --> 22:36.560
is a reason for them

22:36.560 --> 22:37.220
to disappear

22:37.220 --> 22:38.620
that no one would question.

22:40.580 --> 22:42.240
A natural disaster

22:42.240 --> 22:43.540
works just fine.

22:44.040 --> 22:45.260
So does border crossing.

22:45.260 --> 22:47.700
So does geopolitical conflict.

22:52.900 --> 22:54.740
That's when Alex sees it.

22:55.380 --> 22:56.660
A second helicopter,

22:57.060 --> 22:57.780
even bigger,

22:58.100 --> 22:59.240
carrying a steel

22:59.240 --> 23:00.560
Konex shipping container

23:00.560 --> 23:02.600
with a mini-split HVAC unit

23:02.600 --> 23:03.860
bolted to its roof,

23:04.140 --> 23:05.300
slung beneath the chopper

23:05.300 --> 23:06.700
like a coffin on a hook.

23:06.700 --> 23:11.500
According to Barber,

23:11.840 --> 23:13.340
this is how they moved them.

23:13.520 --> 23:14.200
These refugees

23:14.200 --> 23:15.460
aren't being rescued,

23:15.760 --> 23:16.940
they are the cargo.

23:24.140 --> 23:25.920
Three figures materialize

23:25.920 --> 23:26.820
from the dust.

23:27.380 --> 23:30.700
They move fast,

23:30.700 --> 23:31.560
efficient,

23:31.760 --> 23:32.320
predatory.

23:32.580 --> 23:33.700
Alex knows immediately.

23:33.700 --> 23:35.220
These aren't friendlies

23:35.220 --> 23:36.000
coming to help.

23:38.900 --> 23:40.460
Their gear is a Frankenstein

23:40.460 --> 23:42.120
mashup of high-end helmets,

23:42.420 --> 23:42.860
comms,

23:42.940 --> 23:43.800
and lightweight armor.

23:44.080 --> 23:44.920
One guy's pants

23:44.920 --> 23:45.600
are tucked into

23:45.600 --> 23:46.940
his Converse All-Stars.

23:47.940 --> 23:48.980
Does this sound at all

23:48.980 --> 23:50.180
like military to you?

23:52.180 --> 23:54.060
Two men beeline for him

23:54.060 --> 23:55.780
as the third heads up a hill

23:55.780 --> 23:57.120
and shoulders a rifle

23:57.120 --> 23:58.760
aimed at Alex's skull.

23:58.940 --> 24:00.200
And then something happens

24:00.200 --> 24:01.940
that chills Alex's blood.

24:01.940 --> 24:03.480
They call him by name.

24:04.040 --> 24:04.640
Alex!

24:06.480 --> 24:07.980
His stomach drops.

24:08.720 --> 24:10.380
That's when things go sideways.

24:12.100 --> 24:13.780
They rip the rifle from him

24:13.780 --> 24:14.600
and break it down

24:14.600 --> 24:15.400
like a pit crew

24:15.400 --> 24:16.460
before tossing it.

24:23.080 --> 24:24.700
Don't even fucking blink, bro.

24:26.360 --> 24:28.140
He's outgunned three to one

24:28.140 --> 24:29.300
with a rifle pointed

24:29.300 --> 24:30.440
directly at his head

24:30.440 --> 24:31.200
from elevation.

24:31.200 --> 24:36.800
They blindfold Alex

24:36.800 --> 24:38.320
and zip-tie his wrists.

24:39.060 --> 24:40.080
One of them pulls out

24:40.080 --> 24:41.780
a strange handheld device,

24:42.360 --> 24:44.360
something like a bioscanner.

24:44.700 --> 24:46.060
He sweeps Alex with it

24:46.060 --> 24:46.980
from head to toe.

24:50.520 --> 24:52.820
A wand hunting for trackers

24:52.820 --> 24:54.120
and biometric chips?

24:54.360 --> 24:56.460
These guys are professionally trained,

24:56.640 --> 24:58.360
not random desert smugglers.

24:58.360 --> 24:59.960
He doesn't have it.

24:59.960 --> 25:00.900
He doesn't have it.

25:03.900 --> 25:05.300
Man one steps close.

25:05.800 --> 25:07.400
Man three holds the high ground,

25:07.740 --> 25:08.400
rifle steady.

25:08.980 --> 25:10.520
Man one raises his hand,

25:10.940 --> 25:12.040
gives a silent signal,

25:12.480 --> 25:13.860
and somewhere above,

25:14.200 --> 25:15.340
a trigger is pulled.

25:15.340 --> 25:21.760
A 7.62 round tears through Alex's right shoulder,

25:22.020 --> 25:23.460
clavicle pulverized,

25:23.460 --> 25:25.120
shattering bone and flesh.

25:25.120 --> 25:27.780
A second signal and a second shot.

25:27.780 --> 25:29.340
His throat explodes,

25:29.780 --> 25:31.600
drowning in his own blood.

25:31.600 --> 25:36.380
A third signal.

25:36.380 --> 25:37.520
Third shot.

25:37.760 --> 25:38.900
His face is obliterated.

25:39.160 --> 25:40.380
His body drops back,

25:40.620 --> 25:41.900
cold, lifeless,

25:42.320 --> 25:43.360
face to the stars.

25:43.980 --> 25:45.340
Or what's left of his face,

25:45.420 --> 25:45.900
that is.

25:45.900 --> 25:50.500
The entire universe of Alex McEwen

25:50.500 --> 25:52.440
blinked out like a dying star,

25:52.740 --> 25:53.760
sudden and violent.

25:54.160 --> 25:55.540
Children bury their faces.

25:56.040 --> 25:57.780
Some of the women don't look away.

25:58.180 --> 26:00.380
It's almost as if they've seen worse.

26:00.880 --> 26:01.740
Alex McEwen,

26:02.140 --> 26:03.100
tier one operator,

26:03.500 --> 26:03.940
patriot,

26:04.320 --> 26:05.440
now just a corpse

26:05.440 --> 26:06.680
in the Chihuahuan desert.

26:06.680 --> 26:13.180
He believed he died serving his country.

26:13.180 --> 26:14.640
But the men who killed him

26:14.640 --> 26:16.860
were clearly serving something else.

26:25.620 --> 26:27.680
Cut to Pope Air Force Base,

26:27.940 --> 26:28.660
North Carolina.

26:28.880 --> 26:29.800
We're inside

26:29.800 --> 26:31.780
Joint Special Operations Command,

26:32.100 --> 26:32.880
or JSOC,

26:33.120 --> 26:34.240
their operations center.

26:34.240 --> 26:37.120
Everyone's frozen.

26:37.660 --> 26:39.400
The Secretary of Defense himself

26:39.400 --> 26:41.200
is on the other end of the call.

26:41.860 --> 26:43.620
And he is not happy.

26:44.540 --> 26:46.400
Dale, what in the fuck

26:46.400 --> 26:47.720
just happened out there?

26:48.560 --> 26:50.100
General Dale Steinmaker,

26:50.400 --> 26:52.520
commander of Joint Special Operations Command,

26:52.740 --> 26:54.620
is wondering the exact same thing.

26:54.840 --> 26:56.200
Uh, Mr. Secretary,

26:56.500 --> 26:58.540
do you have agency guys

26:58.540 --> 27:00.420
in Coyame, Mexico?

27:01.080 --> 27:02.960
Why the fuck would I?

27:03.140 --> 27:04.200
Everyone's at war.

27:04.420 --> 27:05.060
Nobody should have been

27:05.060 --> 27:06.540
in goddamn Mexico.

27:07.540 --> 27:08.900
But the drone feed

27:08.900 --> 27:10.200
tells a different story.

27:10.700 --> 27:11.980
Someone just took out

27:11.980 --> 27:13.860
an entire special mission unit

27:13.860 --> 27:15.400
on JSOC's watch.

27:15.760 --> 27:16.820
The Predator drone

27:16.820 --> 27:18.960
had caught the whole ugly scene.

27:19.620 --> 27:20.780
Alex's execution,

27:21.360 --> 27:22.900
the refugees being loaded

27:22.900 --> 27:24.160
into the shipping container,

27:24.340 --> 27:25.640
and now the helicopters

27:25.640 --> 27:27.320
lifting off into the desert,

27:27.660 --> 27:29.240
human cargo in tow.

27:29.240 --> 27:30.500
Are you suggesting

27:30.500 --> 27:31.700
this is blue on blue?

27:32.700 --> 27:34.380
Black on block, sir.

27:35.120 --> 27:36.300
Excuse me, gentlemen.

27:39.580 --> 27:41.520
The difference here matters.

27:41.780 --> 27:43.520
Blue on blue is friendly fire.

27:43.860 --> 27:45.400
Tragic, but explainable.

27:45.840 --> 27:47.400
Black on black is a nightmare.

27:47.800 --> 27:48.760
Covert operators

27:48.760 --> 27:50.280
killing covert operators.

27:50.660 --> 27:51.900
Shadow versus shadow.

27:52.360 --> 27:53.340
Whoever did this

27:53.340 --> 27:54.780
wasn't supposed to be there.

27:54.780 --> 27:55.960
The thermal signatures

27:55.960 --> 27:57.120
of six bodies

27:57.120 --> 27:58.560
cool in the sand.

27:59.600 --> 28:01.160
The combat controller

28:01.160 --> 28:02.380
called for air support,

28:02.700 --> 28:03.520
but bled out

28:03.520 --> 28:04.640
mid-sentence.

28:04.640 --> 28:12.280
All right, Vector F-18s

28:12.280 --> 28:13.220
out of white sands.

28:13.380 --> 28:14.960
I want every eye in the sky

28:14.960 --> 28:16.060
on those helicopters.

28:16.700 --> 28:17.560
Wherever they're going,

28:17.800 --> 28:18.900
we're going there first.

28:20.020 --> 28:21.240
Within minutes,

28:21.660 --> 28:23.420
satellites pivot over Koyame.

28:25.800 --> 28:27.700
Half a dozen airborne assets

28:27.700 --> 28:29.600
spin up in Vector South.

28:29.600 --> 28:32.920
Restricted Area 5107,

28:33.200 --> 28:34.880
the largest military installation

28:34.880 --> 28:35.660
in America.

28:35.920 --> 28:37.600
3,200 square miles

28:37.600 --> 28:40.060
of nothing but sand and secrets.

28:40.640 --> 28:42.660
This is where they detonated Trinity,

28:43.100 --> 28:44.520
the first atomic bomb.

28:45.220 --> 28:47.140
July 16th, 1945.

28:49.140 --> 28:50.060
Since then,

28:50.200 --> 28:51.920
it's been a war game's wasteland.

28:55.920 --> 28:57.360
Eagle One and Eagle Two.

28:57.360 --> 28:58.880
Top Gun graduates

28:58.880 --> 29:00.200
yanked off a training mission

29:00.200 --> 29:01.140
and thrown straight

29:01.140 --> 29:02.160
into the real thing.

29:02.640 --> 29:03.240
Eagle Flight,

29:03.380 --> 29:04.300
what is your loadout?

29:06.060 --> 29:06.860
Sorry, gang.

29:06.920 --> 29:07.980
We're fast, but not fatal.

29:08.480 --> 29:09.360
Negative for ordnance.

29:09.640 --> 29:10.800
How about a show of force instead?

29:11.440 --> 29:11.920
Translation?

29:12.340 --> 29:13.440
Scare the hell out of them

29:13.440 --> 29:14.700
and force them to land.

29:15.480 --> 29:16.480
Just don't kill them.

29:16.720 --> 29:17.660
They want answers,

29:18.040 --> 29:18.720
not corpses.

29:25.380 --> 29:26.400
Five miles out,

29:26.400 --> 29:27.620
the helicopters dropped

29:27.620 --> 29:28.400
into a descent.

29:28.720 --> 29:30.340
They sink below the canyon walls

29:30.340 --> 29:31.040
and vanish.

29:33.760 --> 29:35.060
Back in the war room,

29:35.340 --> 29:36.900
the radar blip blinks out.

29:37.200 --> 29:38.500
They lost radar contact.

29:38.960 --> 29:41.000
Radar is line-of-sight technology.

29:41.420 --> 29:42.520
Terrain blocks it.

29:42.900 --> 29:43.740
Fly low enough,

29:44.080 --> 29:45.380
hug the Earth tight enough,

29:45.620 --> 29:46.360
and you disappear.

29:46.940 --> 29:48.680
In skilled aviation circles,

29:48.860 --> 29:49.420
this is called

29:49.420 --> 29:50.860
nap of the Earth flying,

29:50.860 --> 29:52.160
and these pilots know

29:52.160 --> 29:53.580
exactly what they're doing.

29:55.960 --> 29:58.380
Eagle One drops to 8,000 feet.

29:59.980 --> 30:01.880
Night vision goggles on.

30:02.360 --> 30:02.860
Scanning.

30:02.860 --> 30:09.020
Bingo.

30:09.020 --> 30:11.320
Tally 2.

30:11.320 --> 30:14.160
Two helicopters,

30:14.540 --> 30:15.660
and beneath the bigger one,

30:15.820 --> 30:17.340
still spinning on its cable,

30:17.800 --> 30:19.820
the container full of human cargo.

30:21.400 --> 30:22.620
Eagle One calls them out

30:22.620 --> 30:25.160
over guard frequency 243 megahertz,

30:25.160 --> 30:27.660
the international emergency frequency,

30:28.040 --> 30:29.440
and orders them to land.

30:29.980 --> 30:31.080
Copter flight of two

30:31.080 --> 30:31.920
with the external load

30:31.920 --> 30:33.100
east of Coyama in Mexico.

30:33.320 --> 30:34.680
This is a United's Navy F-18.

30:34.940 --> 30:36.260
You are instructed to land immediately.

30:37.160 --> 30:39.340
But the helicopters hold course,

30:39.660 --> 30:41.100
refusing to ID yourself

30:41.100 --> 30:42.900
and ignoring a Navy intercept.

30:43.200 --> 30:43.620
Ballsy.

30:43.620 --> 30:45.860
If this part is true,

30:46.040 --> 30:47.060
we know more about

30:47.060 --> 30:47.880
where to knock

30:47.880 --> 30:48.840
and who to use

30:48.840 --> 30:50.540
the Freedom of Information Act on,

30:50.880 --> 30:53.020
NORAD under U.S. NORTHCOM,

30:53.500 --> 30:56.640
JSOC through U.S. Special Operations Command,

30:57.040 --> 30:57.900
plus the Navy.

31:00.220 --> 31:02.360
And we know what to ask for.

31:02.660 --> 31:04.940
Incident reports and air defense logs

31:04.940 --> 31:06.360
on unknown aircraft

31:06.360 --> 31:08.880
in the Koyama Corridor in 2004

31:08.880 --> 31:12.580
that ignored guard frequency 243 megahertz

31:12.580 --> 31:14.540
and blew off a Navy intercept.

31:16.600 --> 31:17.740
Something I've noticed

31:17.740 --> 31:19.040
doing this show for years

31:19.040 --> 31:20.420
is that the biggest ideas

31:20.420 --> 31:23.640
usually hinge on one strange specific detail.

31:23.820 --> 31:25.640
Gary McKinnon describing a spreadsheet

31:25.640 --> 31:27.660
of non-terrestrial officers.

31:28.320 --> 31:29.520
Hal Puthoff explaining

31:29.520 --> 31:31.120
why CIA remote viewers

31:31.120 --> 31:32.540
tested their abilities

31:32.540 --> 31:34.740
in deep waters on submarines.

31:35.200 --> 31:36.560
Diana Pasolka realizing

31:36.560 --> 31:38.020
that the Vatican Observatory

31:38.020 --> 31:39.880
knew more about UFOs

31:39.880 --> 31:40.900
than met the eye.

31:41.240 --> 31:42.420
These are key details

31:42.420 --> 31:43.920
that completely change

31:43.920 --> 31:45.960
how you understand someone's story.

31:46.160 --> 31:47.220
And if you're not capturing

31:47.220 --> 31:48.120
those details,

31:48.520 --> 31:49.080
they're gone.

31:49.500 --> 31:50.420
I've been getting into

31:50.420 --> 31:52.040
Plod Note Pro lately

31:52.040 --> 31:53.920
exactly for this reason.

31:54.100 --> 31:55.700
Because the same thing happens to me

31:55.700 --> 31:57.200
outside the studio too.

31:57.460 --> 31:58.580
I'll be walking around

31:58.580 --> 31:59.600
thinking through something

31:59.600 --> 32:01.420
a recent guest said on a podcast

32:01.420 --> 32:02.420
and suddenly,

32:02.700 --> 32:03.800
a connection clicks

32:03.800 --> 32:05.300
between that and something

32:05.300 --> 32:06.580
another guest said

32:06.580 --> 32:07.560
two years earlier.

32:07.760 --> 32:09.500
This is one of the clearest examples

32:09.500 --> 32:10.820
I've found personally

32:10.820 --> 32:13.240
of the real utility behind AI.

32:13.240 --> 32:15.820
This product is ridiculously easy to use.

32:16.000 --> 32:17.460
One press to start recording

32:17.460 --> 32:18.740
and then I press it again

32:18.740 --> 32:19.860
to highlight a moment

32:19.860 --> 32:21.060
I want to come back to.

32:21.360 --> 32:23.500
It will take comprehensive notes for you

32:23.500 --> 32:25.380
about everything that transpires.

32:25.620 --> 32:27.780
You can also add text notes or images

32:27.780 --> 32:29.620
so it's not just raw audio

32:29.620 --> 32:30.840
floating around somewhere.

32:31.200 --> 32:32.240
Then when I get back home,

32:32.360 --> 32:34.160
Plod turns everything I've said

32:34.160 --> 32:35.840
into an organized summary

32:35.840 --> 32:37.840
and I can actually ask questions

32:37.840 --> 32:38.960
about what I recorded.

32:39.340 --> 32:40.420
I can ask things like

32:40.420 --> 32:41.740
what was that connection I made

32:41.740 --> 32:43.140
between Thomas Townsend Brown

32:43.140 --> 32:44.020
and time travel?

32:44.100 --> 32:45.180
Or what was that thing I said

32:45.180 --> 32:46.400
around the 10 minute mark

32:46.400 --> 32:47.280
about Bob Lazar?

32:47.620 --> 32:49.060
And Plod will pull the answer

32:49.060 --> 32:50.560
directly from the recording.

32:50.760 --> 32:51.480
That's the difference.

32:51.580 --> 32:53.300
You're not just saving audio.

32:53.560 --> 32:55.500
This isn't your average AI note taker.

32:55.620 --> 32:57.180
You're building a searchable archive

32:57.180 --> 32:58.460
of your own thoughts.

32:58.760 --> 32:59.580
As you can see,

32:59.700 --> 33:01.680
the Note Pro is credit card thin,

33:02.120 --> 33:04.080
has up to 50 hours of battery,

33:04.080 --> 33:06.560
and it handles both in-person conversations

33:06.560 --> 33:07.860
and phone calls

33:07.860 --> 33:09.280
without switching modes.

33:09.640 --> 33:12.160
So head to plod.ai slash alchemy

33:12.160 --> 33:13.160
to learn more.

33:13.460 --> 33:17.040
That's P-L-A-U-D dot A-I slash alchemy

33:17.040 --> 33:19.560
and use code ALCHEMY10 at checkout.

33:19.860 --> 33:20.960
Thanks so much to Plod

33:20.960 --> 33:22.540
for sponsoring today's episode.

33:23.520 --> 33:24.960
But back to the story.

33:26.820 --> 33:28.700
After the intercept doesn't work,

33:28.900 --> 33:30.700
Eagle One decides to get their attention

33:30.700 --> 33:31.960
the old-fashioned way.

33:34.080 --> 33:41.360
But as he lines up the pass,

33:41.700 --> 33:42.500
something's wrong.

33:44.640 --> 33:46.860
The gorge dead ends into a mountain

33:46.860 --> 33:49.280
so massive it eats the stars.

33:49.640 --> 33:52.040
1,500 feet of vertical rock.

33:52.400 --> 33:53.120
No way around,

33:53.400 --> 33:54.320
no way over,

33:54.580 --> 33:55.220
no escape.

33:58.920 --> 34:00.480
So what is this?

34:00.620 --> 34:01.660
A suicide run?

34:01.660 --> 34:06.500
Then everything goes wrong at once.

34:07.320 --> 34:08.140
In the war room,

34:08.260 --> 34:09.460
the drone feed dies.

34:10.680 --> 34:12.200
At the same time,

34:12.340 --> 34:14.280
Eagle One's cockpit goes black.

34:16.440 --> 34:18.220
Flight controls, dead.

34:18.720 --> 34:19.780
Engines, dead.

34:20.320 --> 34:21.780
200 feet from the ground,

34:21.940 --> 34:23.400
at near supersonic speed,

34:23.540 --> 34:25.300
the jet becomes a dead weight.

34:25.300 --> 34:30.480
He has milliseconds to choose.

34:30.820 --> 34:32.620
Ride the coffin into the mountain

34:32.620 --> 34:34.320
or punch out at speeds

34:34.320 --> 34:36.300
that can rip human bodies apart.

34:36.700 --> 34:37.820
The math is ugly.

34:38.160 --> 34:39.720
In an homage to the first man

34:39.720 --> 34:41.480
to ever eject from a cockpit

34:41.480 --> 34:42.960
at supersonic speeds,

34:42.960 --> 34:44.660
he double grips the handle

34:44.660 --> 34:45.620
and pulls.

34:53.120 --> 34:54.880
8,000 feet above,

34:55.180 --> 34:56.540
Eagle Two can't breathe.

34:56.920 --> 34:58.700
His oxygen system is dead.

34:59.040 --> 35:00.060
So are his generators.

35:00.640 --> 35:02.080
He rips off his mask,

35:02.320 --> 35:03.440
fighting through his own

35:03.440 --> 35:04.340
electrical failure.

35:04.880 --> 35:06.360
Systems flicker back online.

35:06.660 --> 35:07.420
He looks down.

35:08.040 --> 35:08.840
The jet's gone,

35:08.840 --> 35:11.080
but the helicopters are still flying

35:11.080 --> 35:12.260
straight at the face

35:12.260 --> 35:13.240
of Mount Mexico.

35:15.560 --> 35:17.420
Nice one here with your barrel in.

35:28.600 --> 35:31.280
The mountainside starts to pixely.

35:31.660 --> 35:34.960
It dissolves from 3D to 2D to nothing

35:34.960 --> 35:37.140
as the helicopters slip through

35:37.140 --> 35:39.500
and vanish from one world into another.

35:40.380 --> 35:41.920
Entering a massive chamber

35:41.920 --> 35:43.860
made of stone and steel beams.

35:44.340 --> 35:46.620
Outside, the electromagnetic force field

35:46.620 --> 35:48.420
re-energizes to the illusion

35:48.420 --> 35:49.620
of solid rock.

35:50.060 --> 35:51.060
To the outside world,

35:51.160 --> 35:52.320
it looks like they vanished.

35:52.740 --> 35:54.800
But inside, they've just arrived.

35:55.140 --> 35:55.440
Home.

35:55.700 --> 35:56.640
Call it a black site,

35:56.820 --> 35:57.760
a breakaway base,

35:57.860 --> 35:58.780
or something worse.

35:59.180 --> 36:00.840
We don't have a name for it yet.

36:01.120 --> 36:02.760
What we do have is a body count

36:02.760 --> 36:03.820
that shouldn't exist.

36:03.820 --> 36:05.340
And a story that leaves

36:05.340 --> 36:06.960
more questions than answers.

36:07.440 --> 36:09.000
An elite American operator

36:09.000 --> 36:10.360
executed in the desert

36:10.360 --> 36:11.560
by unknown forces

36:11.560 --> 36:13.860
using U.S. authentication codes.

36:14.280 --> 36:15.400
A JSOC mission

36:15.400 --> 36:16.980
burned from the inside out.

36:17.480 --> 36:18.400
A weapon system

36:18.400 --> 36:20.440
that can surgically blast drones

36:20.440 --> 36:21.560
and F-18s

36:21.560 --> 36:23.240
with an electromagnetic pulse.

36:24.700 --> 36:25.720
Missing refugees,

36:26.280 --> 36:27.160
human beings,

36:27.620 --> 36:29.120
loaded into a shipping container,

36:29.760 --> 36:31.060
ferried by unmarked helicopters

36:31.660 --> 36:32.820
across the desert,

36:33.260 --> 36:35.120
and chased by U.S. fighter jets

36:35.120 --> 36:37.480
to a holographic mountain in Mexico

36:37.480 --> 36:38.840
that isn't a mountain,

36:39.320 --> 36:40.000
but a door.

36:41.680 --> 36:42.920
And behind it,

36:43.240 --> 36:45.000
a secret underground facility.

36:45.000 --> 36:55.720
The fact that the general

36:55.720 --> 36:58.060
is asking the secretary of defense

36:58.060 --> 36:59.480
if another agency

36:59.480 --> 37:01.380
is running an unsanctioned op

37:01.380 --> 37:02.080
in Mexico

37:02.080 --> 37:04.080
tells us their worst fear.

37:04.080 --> 37:05.700
The enemy isn't foreign.

37:06.280 --> 37:06.960
It's domestic.

37:07.420 --> 37:08.780
But it's not under normal

37:08.780 --> 37:09.880
chains of command.

37:10.260 --> 37:11.180
And if that's true,

37:11.580 --> 37:13.560
then this isn't just a botched mission

37:13.560 --> 37:14.780
in the Koyame Desert.

37:15.580 --> 37:16.920
It's the tip of something

37:16.920 --> 37:17.840
much bigger.

37:19.720 --> 37:21.820
So who's really running this show?

37:22.040 --> 37:23.480
And how deep does this

37:23.480 --> 37:25.160
parallel world actually go?

37:27.680 --> 37:28.900
A real hero.

37:30.420 --> 37:32.360
June 12th, 2023.

37:32.920 --> 37:34.400
The National Press Club event

37:34.400 --> 37:35.760
in Washington, D.C.

37:36.900 --> 37:38.520
After years embedded

37:38.520 --> 37:40.620
in covert crash retrieval operations,

37:41.040 --> 37:41.680
Jake attends

37:41.680 --> 37:43.300
a National Press Club conference

37:43.300 --> 37:44.740
hosted by Stephen Greer.

37:44.880 --> 37:45.380
Thank you.

37:45.480 --> 37:46.860
Stephen Greer is notorious

37:46.860 --> 37:48.120
for getting in touch

37:48.120 --> 37:49.860
with people on the inside

37:49.860 --> 37:51.640
of the UFO Legacy program

37:51.640 --> 37:53.440
and helping draw publicity

37:53.440 --> 37:54.640
to their stories.

37:55.640 --> 37:56.840
Usually, he's going

37:56.840 --> 37:58.940
for the most disgruntled defectors.

37:59.280 --> 38:00.560
Jake shows up at the event

38:00.560 --> 38:02.100
and is there to red team

38:02.100 --> 38:03.040
the whistleblowers.

38:03.580 --> 38:05.440
We were actually sent there

38:05.440 --> 38:08.020
on behalf of our employer

38:08.020 --> 38:10.400
to look for whistleblowers

38:10.400 --> 38:12.400
that we were trying to

38:12.400 --> 38:17.660
basically report to the FBI

38:17.660 --> 38:18.380
and get arrested

38:18.380 --> 38:20.160
because at that time,

38:20.200 --> 38:21.400
I was in this weird place

38:21.400 --> 38:23.920
between becoming a whistleblower

38:23.920 --> 38:27.420
or rounding up the whistleblowers

38:27.420 --> 38:29.220
and shutting them up.

38:30.180 --> 38:32.100
Essentially, figure out what they know,

38:32.500 --> 38:33.420
do a threat assessment,

38:33.420 --> 38:35.120
and report back to headquarters.

38:35.120 --> 38:36.540
Somewhere out there

38:36.540 --> 38:37.740
are a few missing

38:37.740 --> 38:38.980
Panasonic Toughbooks

38:38.980 --> 38:41.360
loaded with highly sensitive material,

38:41.620 --> 38:43.200
and Jake thinks one of these guys

38:43.200 --> 38:44.560
might be about to spill

38:44.560 --> 38:45.300
what's on them.

38:45.780 --> 38:47.340
Then, Michael Herrera

38:47.340 --> 38:48.540
takes the stage.

38:48.920 --> 38:50.040
Herrera was a Marine

38:50.040 --> 38:51.620
with the 31st Marine

38:51.620 --> 38:52.900
Expeditionary Unit.

38:53.460 --> 38:55.740
He described a 2009 mission

38:55.740 --> 38:56.620
in Indonesia,

38:57.280 --> 38:58.800
a civilian evacuation

38:58.800 --> 39:00.440
following a catastrophic

39:00.440 --> 39:01.860
earthquake and tsunami.

39:01.860 --> 39:04.240
Sounds kind of familiar, right?

39:04.700 --> 39:06.960
In 2009, my unit,

39:07.140 --> 39:08.320
which was the most decorated

39:08.320 --> 39:09.420
infantry battalion

39:09.420 --> 39:10.560
in the entire Marine Corps,

39:10.700 --> 39:11.440
which was 2nd Battalion,

39:11.520 --> 39:12.120
5th Marines,

39:12.620 --> 39:13.700
was called in to do

39:13.700 --> 39:15.500
humanitarian assistance operations

39:15.500 --> 39:16.400
out in the Philippines,

39:16.560 --> 39:18.020
which was Operation Kitsana.

39:20.400 --> 39:22.100
His unit was flown deep

39:22.100 --> 39:22.820
into the jungle

39:22.820 --> 39:24.080
with no comms,

39:24.260 --> 39:24.860
no signal,

39:25.140 --> 39:25.920
and no civilians.

39:26.520 --> 39:27.920
His six-man team

39:27.920 --> 39:29.240
pushes to high ground,

39:29.660 --> 39:31.500
to a hill thick with vegetation,

39:31.860 --> 39:33.520
and that's when they see it,

39:34.040 --> 39:34.700
a craft.

39:37.320 --> 39:38.340
And right there

39:38.340 --> 39:39.380
was something that stuck out

39:39.380 --> 39:40.240
like a sore thumb,

39:40.560 --> 39:41.980
especially with jungle terrain,

39:42.100 --> 39:42.720
things like that,

39:42.840 --> 39:43.360
you know,

39:43.720 --> 39:44.400
vegetation,

39:44.600 --> 39:45.480
very green stuff,

39:45.880 --> 39:47.120
was something that stuck out

39:47.120 --> 39:47.680
so well.

39:47.880 --> 39:49.020
It's always going to be

39:49.020 --> 39:50.420
basically imprisoned in my mind

39:50.420 --> 39:51.200
for the rest of my life,

39:51.220 --> 39:52.500
and it has been for 14 years,

39:52.860 --> 39:54.880
was something that was rotating,

39:55.300 --> 39:57.560
and it was transitioning

39:57.560 --> 39:58.400
between colors

39:58.400 --> 40:00.400
like a light matte gray,

40:00.400 --> 40:02.720
as well as a dark matte black.

40:02.900 --> 40:03.580
So in between,

40:03.700 --> 40:04.360
that's what it kept,

40:04.580 --> 40:05.420
and it was very smooth.

40:06.180 --> 40:07.780
You can see that the craft here

40:07.780 --> 40:08.780
actually had,

40:08.860 --> 40:10.820
it was roughly about 300 feet.

40:11.320 --> 40:12.420
And the reason why I know this

40:12.420 --> 40:13.100
is because

40:13.100 --> 40:15.080
you could fit three of the helicopters

40:15.080 --> 40:16.020
that we flew in on

40:16.020 --> 40:17.180
underneath this craft.

40:22.580 --> 40:24.420
300 feet across,

40:25.020 --> 40:26.460
octagonal matte,

40:26.460 --> 40:27.960
or what he describes

40:27.960 --> 40:29.500
as Vanta black.

40:29.920 --> 40:30.720
It's so black

40:30.720 --> 40:31.740
that it almost looks

40:31.740 --> 40:32.620
like dark matter,

40:32.860 --> 40:34.000
like light itself

40:34.000 --> 40:34.980
isn't interacting

40:34.980 --> 40:35.980
with this craft.

40:36.340 --> 40:38.160
It hovers just above the canopy

40:38.160 --> 40:39.720
with a subsonic hum.

40:43.980 --> 40:45.340
Before they can process

40:45.340 --> 40:46.260
what they're looking at,

40:46.340 --> 40:47.280
they're intercepted.

40:48.340 --> 40:50.520
An eight-man paramilitary unit,

40:50.700 --> 40:51.560
no insignias,

40:51.860 --> 40:52.520
no IDs,

40:53.140 --> 40:54.180
moving in fast,

40:54.540 --> 40:55.040
rehearsed,

40:55.040 --> 40:55.960
and ready to kill.

41:01.900 --> 41:03.440
They disarm the Marines,

41:03.740 --> 41:05.140
scan them with a bioscanner,

41:05.340 --> 41:06.780
and hold them at gunpoint.

41:07.140 --> 41:08.140
The message is clear.

41:08.780 --> 41:10.380
You were not supposed to see this,

41:10.640 --> 41:11.520
and if you talk,

41:11.820 --> 41:12.720
we will kill you.

41:13.020 --> 41:13.840
I know what you're thinking.

41:14.160 --> 41:15.280
The Indonesian jungle

41:15.280 --> 41:16.300
sounds a lot like

41:16.300 --> 41:17.220
the Mexican desert.

41:18.680 --> 41:20.160
While this is all happening,

41:20.460 --> 41:22.220
Herrera sees some trucks roll up

41:22.220 --> 41:23.440
with shipping containers

41:23.440 --> 41:25.460
and HVACs mounted on top.

41:27.880 --> 41:30.180
He assumed they were moving drugs,

41:30.560 --> 41:32.600
but hearing Michael Herrera's testimony,

41:33.180 --> 41:33.960
Jake knew better.

41:34.120 --> 41:35.320
He had the missing piece

41:35.320 --> 41:36.260
of Michael's puzzle.

41:36.260 --> 41:40.440
I have no first-hand experience

41:40.440 --> 41:41.780
with that operation,

41:42.040 --> 41:43.720
nor direct contact

41:43.720 --> 41:47.180
with anyone involved with it.

41:47.360 --> 41:49.460
I know of that type of operation.

41:49.620 --> 41:50.700
I know of that craft.

41:50.820 --> 41:52.000
I know of those containers.

41:52.600 --> 41:54.480
He'd seen those containers before.

41:54.900 --> 41:56.560
Those units that they used

41:56.560 --> 41:58.100
are consistent with the workstations

41:58.100 --> 41:59.680
we use when we're out on the range.

41:59.920 --> 42:01.920
There are many split HVAC systems

42:01.920 --> 42:02.800
that are used up there.

42:02.800 --> 42:05.340
And they weren't hauling drugs.

42:05.700 --> 42:06.760
They were hauling people.

42:07.100 --> 42:07.460
Kids.

42:07.820 --> 42:09.800
There are operations OCONUS

42:09.800 --> 42:12.000
outside the continental United States

42:12.000 --> 42:15.480
where prospecting for psionic assets

42:15.480 --> 42:16.200
takes place,

42:16.260 --> 42:17.220
and they're highly coveted.

42:17.340 --> 42:18.620
And the interesting thing is,

42:19.000 --> 42:21.320
is I hear in those programs

42:21.320 --> 42:24.180
that there's something valuable

42:24.180 --> 42:25.480
about the life experience

42:25.480 --> 42:26.720
in third-world countries

42:26.720 --> 42:29.700
in that it seems as though

42:29.700 --> 42:31.640
people that live a simpler life

42:31.640 --> 42:32.820
and are outdoors more

42:32.820 --> 42:34.480
and have less contaminants

42:34.480 --> 42:35.780
in their food and their drugs

42:35.780 --> 42:36.560
and in their culture

42:36.560 --> 42:38.620
seem to be a little bit better

42:38.620 --> 42:39.840
at disassociating

